{"add":{"doc":{"id":"0ee167b93312e503046d12039e4ee211df4b8ce82058c5f4289d0169f6d115f0","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Determinant_example.svg/300px-Determinant_example.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["The determinant det(A) or |A| of a square matrix A is a number encoding certain properties of the matrix. A matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is nonzero. Its absolute value equals the area (in R2) or volume (in R3) of the image of the unit square (or cube), while its sign corresponds to the orientation of the corresponding linear map: the determinant is positive if and only if the orientation is preserved."]}}}